<font color="#FF0000">ANOTHER MYTH IS BORN</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 11  1:11:18 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Paul<br>
Your post reminded me of Tin Man.<br><br>
Tin man woke up one day with a stiff neck. The corpsmen assigned to our platoon placed him on light duty for a couple of days and so Tin Man  got out of having to go on patrols or having to fill sand bags. Tin Man somehow stretched it out for a whole week and then some. <br>
He was a great guy but found out that by faking an injury he could get out of doing some other unpleasant tasks. <br>
Last year I spoke to a Marine that had arrived in Nam months after I had left and well over a year since Tin Man had been there. Yet, the Marine spoke of the exploits of Tin Man as if he knew him. Tin Man because of his exploits had become a legend in Vietnam. <br><br>
I guess MTF is like that and I guess that’s another way how myths and legends are born. Now, did I ever tell you about Nasty Nick? Batman? Lucky, who really wasn't very lucky? All these men became legions and won our honor in one way or another. But then I guess that's another way how myths are made.<br><br>
Today little Pagemaker, some high school kid, heard what you had to say and if it made you feel proud of what you shared, he took it to heart and will honor his country by volunteering to serve. Then one day he’ll repeat what you said to others and another myth will be born.  But of course he’ll change it a little and make you a bare footed Marine carrying an M-60, with a K-bar in your mouth and a dozen grenades hanging from your shirt pockets while you hung from the skids of a chopper and shot at the enemy from tree top level. Yet that’s the way myths are born, It all starts at our educational institution. <br>

